Face Recognition - Problem Statement¶

Context¶

Company X owns a movie application and repository that caters to movie streaming to millions of users on a subscription basis. The company wants to automate the process of cast and crew information in each scene from a movie such that when a user pauses on the movie and clicks on the cast information button, the app will show details of the actor in the scene. The company has in-house computer vision and multimedia experts who need to detect faces from screenshots of the movie scene.

Objective¶

  • Part A: To build a face detection system

  • Part B: To create an image dataset to be used by the AI team to build image classifier data

  • Part C: To build a face recognition system

Part A¶

  • label: Identifies the object in the image

  • notes: Additional comments (currently empty)

  • points: Co-ordinates of the mask (top-left and bottom-right)

  • imageWidth: Width of the image in pixels

  • imageHeight: Height of the image in pixels

Part B¶

The dataset comprises facial images that may contain either multiple individuals or a single individual per image.

Part C¶

This dataset consists of 10,770 images collected from Pinterest, featuring 100 individuals.

Split the images and their mask into two objects¶

In [ ]:
# splitting the image and mask into two objects
IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH = 128, 128

processed_images = []
processed_masks = []

for img, points in images:
    if img is None or len(img.shape) < 2:
        continue

    try:
        # Resize image
        resized_img = cv2.resize(img, (IMG_WIDTH, IMG_HEIGHT), interpolation=cv2.INTER_AREA)

        # Fix channels
        if len(resized_img.shape) == 2:
            resized_img = cv2.cvtColor(resized_img, cv2.COLOR_GRAY2RGB)
        elif resized_img.shape[2] == 4:
            resized_img = cv2.cvtColor(resized_img, cv2.COLOR_RGBA2RGB)

        if resized_img.shape != (IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3):
            print(f"Skipping image with unexpected shape: {resized_img.shape}")
            continue

        # ✅ Create blank mask for the original image size
        mask = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1]), dtype=np.uint8)

        for point_info in points:
            points_list = point_info.get("points", [])
            if isinstance(points_list, list) and len(points_list) == 2:
                try:
                    x1 = int(points_list[0]["x"] * img.shape[1])
                    y1 = int(points_list[0]["y"] * img.shape[0])
                    x2 = int(points_list[1]["x"] * img.shape[1])
                    y2 = int(points_list[1]["y"] * img.shape[0])

                    # Validate coordinates
                    if 0 <= x1 < x2 <= img.shape[1] and 0 <= y1 < y2 <= img.shape[0]:
                        mask[y1:y2, x1:x2] = 255

                except Exception as e:
                    print(f"Error parsing coordinates: {e}")

        # ✅ Resize mask to match image
        resized_mask = cv2.resize(mask, (IMG_WIDTH, IMG_HEIGHT), interpolation=cv2.INTER_NEAREST)

        # Append both
        processed_images.append(resized_img)
        processed_masks.append(resized_mask)

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error during processing: {e}")

Part I: Model Building and Evaluation¶

Design a face mask detection model¶

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Conv2DTranspose, concatenate
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

def build_unet_model(input_shape=(128, 128, 3)):
    inputs = Input(input_shape)

    # Encoder
    c1 = Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(inputs)
    c1 = Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c1)
    p1 = MaxPooling2D()(c1)

    c2 = Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(p1)
    c2 = Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c2)
    p2 = MaxPooling2D()(c2)

    c3 = Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(p2)
    c3 = Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c3)
    p3 = MaxPooling2D()(c3)

    # Bottleneck
    c4 = Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(p3)
    c4 = Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c4)

    # Decoder
    u5 = Conv2DTranspose(64, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c4)
    u5 = concatenate([u5, c3])
    c5 = Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(u5)
    c5 = Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c5)

    u6 = Conv2DTranspose(32, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c5)
    u6 = concatenate([u6, c2])
    c6 = Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(u6)
    c6 = Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c6)

    u7 = Conv2DTranspose(16, 2, strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c6)
    u7 = concatenate([u7, c1])
    c7 = Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(u7)
    c7 = Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu', padding='same')(c7)

    outputs = Conv2D(1, 1, activation='sigmoid')(c7)

    model = Model(inputs=[inputs], outputs=[outputs])
    return model

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import load_img, img_to_array

# Load and preprocess image
# Make sure the target_size matches the model's input size
img = load_img(img_path, target_size=(128, 128))
img_array = img_to_array(img) / 255.0  # Normalize to [0, 1]
img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0)  # Shape: (1, 128, 128, 3)

# Predict segmentation mask
pred_mask = model.predict(img_array, verbose=0)[0]  # Shape: (128, 128, 1)

# Threshold the mask
binary_mask = (pred_mask > 0.5).astype(np.uint8) # Shape should be (128, 128, 1)

# Ensure the mask is 2D for plotting
# Check shape and squeeze/reshape if needed
if binary_mask.ndim == 3 and binary_mask.shape[-1] == 1:
    # If it's (M, N, 1), squeeze to (M, N)
    mask_to_plot = binary_mask.squeeze(axis=-1)
elif binary_mask.ndim == 2:
    # If it's already (M, N), use directly
    mask_to_plot = binary_mask
else:
    # Unexpected shape, print info and skip plotting the mask or handle error
    print(f"Warning: Predicted mask has unexpected shape {binary_mask.shape}. Cannot plot mask.")
    mask_to_plot = None # Or raise an error

# Plot original image and predicted mask
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

# Original image
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(img) # Plot the PIL image directly or img_array[0]
plt.title("Original Image")
plt.axis("off")

# Predicted mask
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
if mask_to_plot is not None:
    # Print the actual shape being passed to imshow for debugging
    print(f"Shape of mask passed to imshow: {mask_to_plot.shape}")
    plt.imshow(mask_to_plot, cmap="gray")
    plt.title("Predicted Mask")
    plt.axis("off")
else:
    # Placeholder if mask could not be plotted
    plt.title("Mask Plotting Failed")
    plt.text(0.5, 0.5, "Mask shape error", horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='center')
    plt.axis("off")


plt.tight_layout()

Detect faces, extract metadata for the faces in all the images, and write and save it into a DataFrame¶

In [ ]:
import cv2
import pandas as pd

# Load Haar cascade face detector
face_cascade = cv2.CascadeClassifier(cv2.data.haarcascades + 'haarcascade_frontalface_default.xml')

metadata = []

# Loop through all extracted images
for file in os.listdir(extract_folder):
    if file.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png')):
        image_path = os.path.join(extract_folder, file)
        image = cv2.imread(image_path)

        if image is None:
            print(f"Skipped unreadable image: {file}")
            continue

        gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
        faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray, scaleFactor=1.1, minNeighbors=5)

        for (x, y, w, h) in faces:
            metadata.append({
                'image_name': file,
                'x': x,
                'y': y,
                'width': w,
                'height': h
            })

# Save metadata to CSV
df = pd.DataFrame(metadata)
csv_output_path = '/content/face_metadata.csv'
df.to_csv(csv_output_path, index=False)
print(f"✅ Face metadata saved to {csv_output_path}")

✅ Face metadata saved to /content/face_metadata.csv

# Generate embeddings
def get_embedding(img_path):
    try:
        img = load_img(img_path, target_size=(224, 224))
        img_array = img_to_array(img)
        img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0)
        img_array = preprocess_input(img_array)
        features = model.predict(img_array, verbose=0)
        return features.flatten()
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error loading {img_path}: {e}")
        return None

from tensorflow.keras.applications import MobileNetV2
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2 import preprocess_input
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import load_img, img_to_array
import numpy as np

# Load pre-trained model (excluding top layer, using global average pooling)
model = MobileNetV2(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')

def get_embedding(img_path):
    try:
        img = load_img(img_path, target_size=(224, 224))
        img_array = img_to_array(img)
        img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0)
        img_array = preprocess_input(img_array)

        embedding = model.predict(img_array, verbose=0)
        return embedding.flatten()
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Failed for {img_path}: {e}")
        return None

import os
import pandas as pd

base_folder = '/content/PINS_data/PINS'  # Adjust if needed
image_paths = []
labels = []

for folder in os.listdir(base_folder):
    folder_path = os.path.join(base_folder, folder)
    if os.path.isdir(folder_path):
        for img_file in os.listdir(folder_path):
            if img_file.lower().endswith(('.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png')):
                image_paths.append(os.path.join(folder_path, img_file))
                labels.append(folder)

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'filename': image_paths,
    'label': labels
})

In [ ]:



    


from tensorflow.keras.utils import load_img, img_to_array
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet_v2 import preprocess_input
from tensorflow.keras.applications import MobileNetV2
import numpy as np
from tqdm import tqdm

# Load model once
model = MobileNetV2(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, pooling='avg')

BATCH_SIZE = 64  # Try 64 or 128, depending on memory
IMG_SIZE = (224, 224)

# Prepare batches
image_paths = df['filename'].tolist()
all_embeddings = []
valid_paths = []

for i in tqdm(range(0, len(image_paths), BATCH_SIZE), desc="Batch processing"):
    batch_paths = image_paths[i:i+BATCH_SIZE]
    batch_images = []

    for path in batch_paths:
        try:
            img = load_img(path, target_size=IMG_SIZE)
            img_array = img_to_array(img)
            batch_images.append(img_array)
            valid_paths.append(path)
        except:
            print(f"Skipping {path}")

    if batch_images:
        batch_images = np.array(batch_images)
        batch_images = preprocess_input(batch_images)
        batch_embeddings = model.predict(batch_images, verbose=0)
        all_embeddings.extend(batch_embeddings)

# Convert to array
embeddings = np.array(all_embeddings)
print("✅ Total embeddings generated:", embeddings.shape)

from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_distances
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from PIL import Image

# Choose a sample image (e.g., index 0)
sample_index = 0
sample_embedding = embeddings[sample_index].reshape(1, -1)
distances = cosine_distances(sample_embedding, embeddings).flatten()

# Sort and get top 5 closest (excluding itself)
similar_indices = np.argsort(distances)[1:6]

# Display sample + top 5 similar
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 6, 1)
plt.imshow(Image.open(valid_paths[sample_index]))
plt.title("Query")
plt.axis('off')

for i, idx in enumerate(similar_indices):
    plt.subplot(1, 6, i+2)
    plt.imshow(Image.open(valid_paths[idx]))
    plt.title(f"Sim #{i+1}")
    plt.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Get labels for only valid image paths (used in embeddings)
valid_df = df[df['filename'].isin(valid_paths)].reset_index(drop=True)
labels = valid_df['label']

# Encode labels to integers
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

le = LabelEncoder()
y = le.fit_transform(labels)

# Train-test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(embeddings, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y)



    















Apply PCA¶












In [ ]:



    


from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

from sklearn.svm import SVC

Insights from analysis¶
    

  • Low Classification Accuracy
Despite using deep features extracted from MobileNetV2 and various classifiers (SVM, Random Forest), the overall classification accuracy remained below 32%, indicating the model’s limited ability to distinguish between identities in the current setup.
    

    • 

  • High Class Imbalance
The dataset contains a large number of classes (over 100+ identities), many of which have very few samples (e.g., <20). This makes it difficult for classifiers to learn reliable patterns for those labels.
    

    • 

  • Some Classes Perform Well
A few identities (e.g., Morgan Freeman, Sundar Pichai, Chadwick Boseman) consistently show higher performance, likely due to clearer, consistent facial features and sufficient number of images.
    

    • 

  • Certain Classes Have 0 Recall/Precision
Some identities (e.g., Shakira, Maria Pedraza, Lindsey Morgan) were never predicted correctly, suggesting either: Very few training samples, Poor image quality, Mislabelled or inconsistent data.
    

    • 

  • Simple Classifiers May Not Be Sufficient
Traditional machine learning classifiers like SVM and Random Forest are not scaling well with the high-dimensional embedding space and multi-class scenario.
    

    • 



Actionable Business Recommendations¶
    

  • Remove underrepresented classes with fewer than 20 images, Focus only on top-performing classes to improve model generalization and reduce noise.
    

    • 

  • Perform data cleaning: remove mislabeled, blurred, or duplicate images, Augment minority class samples with image augmentation techniques (e.g., flip, crop, brightness change) to reduce class imbalance.
    

    • 

  • Replace Random Forest or SVM with XGBoost, which performs better with imbalanced data and large feature datasets.
